{"hits": {"hits": [{"created": "2026-01-08T01:17:37.281123+00:00", "modified": "2026-01-08T01:17:37.795770+00:00", "id": 18180017, "conceptrecid": "18180016", "doi": "10.5281/zenodo.18180017", "conceptdoi": "10.5281/zenodo.18180016", "doi_url": "https://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.18180017", "metadata": {"title": "Insect pest monitoring with camera-equipped traps: strengths and limitations", "doi": "10.5281/zenodo.18180017", "publication_date": "2021", "description": "(Uploaded by Plazi for the IPBES Invasive Alien Species Assessment) Integrated pest management relies on insect pest monitoring to support the decision of counteracting a given level of infestation and to select the adequate control method. The classic monitoring approach of insect pests is based on placing in single infested areas a series of traps that are checked by human operators on a temporal basis. This strategy requires high labor cost and provides poor spatial and temporal resolution achievable by single operators. The adoption of image sensors to monitor insect pests can result in several practical advantages. The purpose of this review is to summarize the progress made on automatic traps with a particular focus on camera-equipped traps. The use of software and image recognition algorithms can support automatic trap usage to identify and/or count insect species from pictures. Considering the high image resolution achievable and the opportunity to exploit data transfer systems through wireless technology, it is possible to have remote control of insect captures, limiting field visits. The availability of real-time and on-line pest monitoring systems from a distant location opens the opportunity for measuring insect population dynamics constantly and simultaneously in a large number of traps with a limited human labor requirement. The actual limitations are the high cost, the low power autonomy and the low picture quality of some prototypes together with the need for further improvements in fully automated pest detection. Limits and benefits resulting from several case studies are examined with a perspective for the future development of technology-driven insect pest monitoring and management.", "access_right": "restricted", "creators": [{"name": "Preti, Michele", "affiliation": null}, {"name": "Verheggen, Fran\u00e7ois", "affiliation": null}, {"name": "Angeli, Sergio", "affiliation": null}], "keywords": ["Chapter 5", "biodiversity", "environment assessment", "IPBES", "Alien Invasive Species Assessment AIS", "invasive species"], "related_identifiers": [{"identifier": "hash://md5/9dc6c8624c95a1918a649e9b0b1c69b0", "relation": "hasVersion", "scheme": "url"}, {"identifier": "hash://sha256/49fd1f369ec8bb3b6e86347ba1cd402a6d6c404492ff3aa648b5f9bd3c12db51", "relation": "hasVersion", "scheme": "url"}, {"identifier": "zotero://select/groups/2352922/items/VTPXBN9T", "relation": "isDerivedFrom", "scheme": "url"}, {"identifier": "https://zotero.org/groups/2352922/items/VTPXBN9T", "relation": "isDerivedFrom", "scheme": "url"}, {"identifier": "https://linker.bio/cut:hash://md5/2856c658a635daf344f7958f785111e8!/b191548-193710", "relation": "isDerivedFrom", "scheme": "url"}, {"identifier": "hash://md5/359bd494433933b868f85e88d3437f76", "relation": "isPartOf", "scheme": "url"}, {"identifier": "10.1007/s10340-020-01309-4", "relation": "isVariantFormOf", "resource_type": "publication", "scheme": "doi"}, {"identifier": "10.5281/zenodo.7430682", "relation": "isCitedBy", "resource_type": "publication-report", "scheme": "doi"}, {"identifier": "10.5281/zenodo.1410543", "relation": "isCompiledBy", "resource_type": "software", "scheme": "doi"}], "resource_type": {"title": "Journal article", "type": "publication", "subtype": "article"}, "journal": {"issue": "2", "pages": "203-217", "title": "Journal of Pest Science", "volume": "94"}, "alternate_identifiers": [{"identifier": "hash://md5/9dc6c8624c95a1918a649e9b0b1c69b0"}, {"identifier": "urn:lsid:zotero.org:groups:2352922:items:VTPXBN9T